newsitem.title: USA: U.S. cash soymeal - Stronger futures slow movement.
newsitem.headline: U.S. cash soymeal - Stronger futures slow movement.

text.p: U.S. rail and truck cash soymeal basis offers were flat to lower Thursday as rising CBOT prices curbed buying interest, cash soymeal brokers said.
"It's kind of putting a chokehold" on movement, a broker said of the strength in CBOT futures. "It's keeping people from jumping in there and doing anything extra."
The CBOT Sept soymeal contract rose $1.50 at $257.20 a ton at 1045 CDT compared with a recent low of $234.00 on Aug 9.
CIF and FOB markets were steady. Soymeal exports totaled 69,700 tonnes in the week ended Aug 15 versus 91,800 the week before, USDA reported.
Total exports for the year were 3.76 million tonnes, behind last year's pace of 4.24 million.
On the supply side, brokers said they expected two Iowa processors to resume production in the next week after taking seasonal downtimes.

Brokers estimated the soybean crush in the week ended Wednesday would range from 22.0 million to 23.0 million bushels of soybeans. Processors crushed 22.37 million bushels the week earlier, according to the National Oilseed Processors Association.
